## Table 2 — cc_horizon_tags

Stores scenario tags independently from draft and version records. One row per founder per horizon per context (draft or version). Keeping this separate allows tags to be updated without rewriting the full draft or version record.

```sql
create table cc_horizon_tags (
  id                  uuid primary key default gen_random_uuid(),
  user_id             uuid not null references auth.users(id) on delete cascade,
  horizon             text not null check (horizon in ('12_month', '24_month', '36_month', 'ultimate_vision')),
  context             text not null check (context in ('draft', 'version')),
  context_id          uuid not null,
  scenario_id         uuid references gvs_saved_growth_scenarios(id) on delete set null,
  scenario_snapshot   jsonb,
  tagged_at           timestamptz not null default now(),

  unique (user_id, horizon, context, context_id)
);

-- Indexes
create index cc_horizon_tags_user_id_idx on cc_horizon_tags(user_id);
create index cc_horizon_tags_context_id_idx on cc_horizon_tags(context_id);
create index cc_horizon_tags_scenario_id_idx on cc_horizon_tags(scenario_id);

-- RLS
alter table cc_horizon_tags enable row level security;

create policy "Users can manage their own horizon tags"
  on cc_horizon_tags
  for all
  using (auth.uid() = user_id)
  with check (auth.uid() = user_id);
```

**Notes:**

`context` distinguishes whether this tag belongs to a draft record or a version record. `context_id` is the UUID of the relevant `cc_drafts.id` or `cc_versions.id` record.

`scenario_snapshot` stores a point-in-time copy of the relevant scenario data at the time of tagging — GVI score, band label, composition label, pressure profile summary, and GPT synthesis excerpt. This prevents the synthesis from changing retroactively if the founder later modifies or deletes the original scenario.

