## Table 6 — cc_synthesis_log

Logs every GPT synthesis call. One row per call. Never updated after creation. Provides operational visibility into synthesis generation, cost tracking, error logging, and the input hash comparison logic that drives the regenerate decision.

```sql
create table cc_synthesis_log (
  id                  uuid primary key default gen_random_uuid(),
  user_id             uuid not null references auth.users(id) on delete cascade,
  version_id          uuid references cc_versions(id) on delete set null,
  input_hash          text not null,
  trigger             text not null check (trigger in ('submit', 'regenerate')),
  status              text not null default 'pending' check (status in ('pending', 'success', 'failed')),
  error_message       text,
  tokens_used         integer,
  model               text,
  duration_ms         integer,
  created_at          timestamptz not null default now(),
  completed_at        timestamptz
);

-- Indexes
create index cc_synthesis_log_user_id_idx on cc_synthesis_log(user_id);
create index cc_synthesis_log_version_id_idx on cc_synthesis_log(version_id);
create index cc_synthesis_log_input_hash_idx on cc_synthesis_log(user_id, input_hash);

-- RLS
alter table cc_synthesis_log enable row level security;

create policy "Users can read their own synthesis log"
  on cc_synthesis_log
  for select
  using (auth.uid() = user_id);

create policy "Service role can insert synthesis log entries"
  on cc_synthesis_log
  for insert
  with check (true);
```

**Notes:**

`trigger` distinguishes between an initial submit call and a regenerate call. Useful for analytics and cost attribution.

`tokens_used`, `model`, and `duration_ms` enable cost tracking per synthesis call. These are populated by the n8n workflow after the GPT call completes.

The insert policy uses `with check (true)` because synthesis log entries are written by the n8n service role, not by the authenticated user directly.

